  "datePublished": "2026-03-31",
  "description": "The cosmic microwave background (CMB) is thermal radiation left over from recombination, approximately 380,000 years after the Big Bang \u0026ndash; the oldest light in the universe, now cooled by the expansion of space from roughly 3,000 kelvin to 2.725 kelvin, placing it in the microwave band of the electromagnetic spectrum.\nBefore recombination, the universe was a hot plasma of free electrons and atomic nuclei. Photons scattered constantly off free electrons and could not travel far \u0026ndash; the universe was opaque, like the interior of a star. When the universe cooled enough for electrons to combine with nuclei into neutral atoms, photons were freed. The CMB is the light from that moment, arriving from every direction in the sky.\n",
  "name": "Cosmic Microwave Background",
